review:
3030 is a really cool, fun game. I really appreciated the retro vibe that it goes after.  

Here's what I liked:

// The graphics are sweet, and also the most immediate throwback to the retro vibe that gives this game a sense of nostalgia while still being original.

// The music is a really nice touch.  I'll admit, I was a little weirded out when I was first playing and suddenly the music had lyrics.  I can't think of any games I've played, at least anytime recently, where the music had lyrics.  So I thought that was a strange choice, until I looked a little deeper and learned that the bulk of the music in the game is performed by The Kyoto Connection (TKC), a sort of electro/synth pop group from Argentina.  This was an appropriate choice for music in the end, since many of the synthy electronic sounds in their music, combined with the pop-ish singing, lends itself very well to the type of game that 3030 is, even if some find it a little unusual.

// There are some obvious character inspirations in the game, which is not necessarily needed but definitely very cool.  The main character could easily be a cross between Indiana Jones, and Lone Star.

// The gameplay is fun enough to play casually without being too deeply involved, and the plot is entertaining, with the potential to be so much larger, which leads me to my next thing..

Here's what I didn't like so much:

// The story, while short enough to be easily digestible, is very short in a way that I found disappointing. Don't get me wrong, I really enjoyed the story.  It's just way too short.  To the credit of the developers, they don't overstate the game as being this big, epic thing. But by the time I completed the story, with a ship that the game had given me less than halfway through (which I didn't even want), I just felt like it was not only too easy but also too short.  What I'm saying, really, is that I feel the story could have been much more expansive, especially given how many systems there are to explore, and yet you only go to maybe half of them throughout the story.

// 3030 has much less replay value than what I first expected.  After completing the story, there really isn't much point to playing the game, unless you feel like grinding low-value missions to save up enough space credits to get a ship that you actually wanted, which I did do, by the way.  But afterwards, I played for another 10 minutes before turning it off.  The ship I saved up for and bought was cool, but there just wasn't any reason to fly it anymore, other than for the sake of passing time before playing the next game.

TLDR; It's a really fun game, and I might have missed mentioning some mechanics that make it cool, but that's not really relevant--it's definitely worth the asking price and even though the story is short, I still played it for a good bit of time (4-6 hrs) after finishing it.  Definitely recommend, even at full price, and would love to see if any more story content is added later. Cheers to the devs for creating a game they wanted to create.
